WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.040
Hello and welcome back. In this video, I will show you how to use OpenClaw to bypass trial period.

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:13.660
I'm going to use this crack me called days remaining. When I run it, it shows the trial

00:00:13.660 --> 00:00:22.720
period remaining. I want to patch it so that it never expires. I start x64dbg which is a 32-bit

00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:36.400
version as administrator. Next, I open the target CrackMe. In Telegram, I ask OpenClaw to list some

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:50.250
Win32 API that checks for time or date. It lists down some API. Let's try GetLocalTime. I copy its

00:00:50.250 --> 00:01:00.250
name. Back in x64dbg, I right-click and search for current module intermodular calls. There is a long

00:01:00.250 --> 00:01:08.750
list in the search results. I then filter out, get local time. There are four results. So I add

00:01:08.750 --> 00:01:17.900
breakpoints on all of them, select all four, right click and toggle breakpoint. Then click on the

00:01:17.900 --> 00:01:24.120
breakpoints tab to confirm and right now we see that hits are zero. Run the debugger and one of

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:32.960
the breakpoints is hit. The program shows the window with the message trial period remaining

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:38.840
2. I double click on the breakpoint address that was hit and that takes me to the location

00:01:38.840 --> 00:01:44.900
where the getLocalTime API was triggered. Scrolling up, I take note the start of this

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:51.820
function at the instruction push EBP. I scroll down and look for the RET instruction which marks

00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:59.240
the end of the function. In Telegram, I ask OpenClaw to connect to the debugger using MCP

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:02.140
and to refer to memory on how to do that.

00:02:05.310 --> 00:02:09.830
It then replies saying it is ready to connect and lists down the method to do so.

00:02:10.250 --> 00:02:16.030
I then copy the address of the start of the function by right-clicking and selecting copy address.

00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:24.720
I then ask OpenClaw to disassemble the function and paste in the address.

00:02:25.180 --> 00:02:33.360
I also ask it to understand how remaining days is calculated and to show me the lines where it does so.

00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:37.440
OpenClaw goes to work.

00:02:37.660 --> 00:02:43.420
And bit by bit, it disassembles the binary, analyzes it, and reports back its findings.

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:49.300
Finally, it shows me the instructions where remaining days are being calculated.

00:02:49.640 --> 00:02:52.680
I copy those lines and ask it to explain them.

00:02:57.050 --> 00:02:59.910
OpenClaw then gives an in-depth explanation.

00:03:00.470 --> 00:03:08.970
Basically, the target program is taking the constant 28, which in hex is 1c, and deducting 28 from the current day of the week.

00:03:08.970 --> 00:03:17.380
I then ask it what is the maximum possible days remaining.

00:03:17.380 --> 00:03:24.810
It then performs some calculation and informs me that the maximum is 28.

00:03:24.810 --> 00:03:36.390
I then ask it which instruction limits the remaining days to 28 days maximum.

00:03:36.390 --> 00:03:42.670
It then tells me that the instruction move EAX, 1C sets the maximum to 28 because it loads

00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:46.290
the constant 28 to be used in the calculation.

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:51.670
I ask it what other values could be loaded instead of 1C that would affect the maximum

00:03:51.670 --> 00:03:59.140
days remaining.

00:03:59.140 --> 00:04:04.880
And it gives a list of examples that could be used instead of 1C and concludes by saying

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:13.690
that whatever replaces 1C becomes the new ceiling for the days remaining calculation.

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:23.090
I then ask it if we use 0xFF, which in decimal is 255, what would be the maximum days remaining.

00:04:23.090 --> 00:04:27.850
It replies saying the maximum would be 255 days.

00:04:27.850 --> 00:04:34.460
I will now modify the code to replace 1c with ff.

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:40.900
Copy the address of the target instruction.

00:04:40.900 --> 00:04:46.380
In the debugger, right click and select go to expression.

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:49.970
Paste in the address.

00:04:49.970 --> 00:04:54.330
To modify this instruction, press spacebar.

00:04:54.330 --> 00:05:01.370
Or you can right click and select assemble.

00:05:01.370 --> 00:05:06.130
Change the constant from 0x1c to 0xff.

00:05:06.130 --> 00:05:11.050
Click the checkbox, keep size so that it will not overwrite the next instruction.

00:05:11.050 --> 00:05:18.530
To patch it, click on file then patch file.

00:05:18.530 --> 00:05:25.350
Give a new name with "-v2", at the end of the file name.

00:05:25.350 --> 00:05:28.270
This will be version 2.

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:32.660
Close the debugger.

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:37.780
Run the patch file and we get 229 days remaining.

00:05:37.780 --> 00:05:40.200
Previously, it was 2 days.

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:41.580
So it works.

00:05:41.580 --> 00:05:45.880
So this is how we can use OpenCLAW to bypass trial periods.

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:47.380
That's all for this video.

00:05:47.380 --> 00:05:48.280
Thanks for watching.

